x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Goldman Sachs is ba=
ck, baby! Or at least that=E2=80=99s the conclusion of <b>Mike Mayo</b>, th=
e influential Wall Street analyst at Wells Fargo, and it=E2=80=99s hard to =
disagree. Twenty-five years after the firm=E2=80=99s May 1999 I.P.O., Goldm=
an=E2=80=99s stock is trading at or near its all-time high, and has a marke=
t value of almost $150 billion, narrowing the once-yawning valuation gap wi=
th rival Morgan Stanley to around $10 billion. Goldman=E2=80=99s first-quar=
ter performance delighted Mayo and other Wall Street research analysts, and=
 the outlook for the rest of the year seems bright, given the pickup in the=
 financing and M&amp;A markets. =E2=80=9CThey=E2=80=99re crushing it in the=
ir legacy business, global banking and markets, and that=E2=80=99s two-thir=
ds of the company,=E2=80=9D Mayo told me. =E2=80=9CAnd the other one-third =
of the company, which is wealth and asset management, is on its way toward =
a
mid-teens return.=E2=80=9D</td>
