          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">Not surprisingly, <=
b>John Waldron</b>, Goldman=E2=80=99s chief operating officer and Solomon=
=E2=80=99s second-in-command, agreed with Mayo=E2=80=99s upbeat view of Gol=
dman and its near-term prospects. In a recent interview, he told me that =
=E2=80=9Cturning the page=E2=80=9D on Goldman=E2=80=99s failed forays into =
consumer banking =E2=80=9Cmade it clear to everybody, particularly internal=
ly=E2=80=9D that Goldman Sachs was =E2=80=9Cnarrowing our focus back on are=
as where we have reasons to be very, very strong.=E2=80=9D He said that sho=
wing its money-losing financials in the consumer business separately starti=
ng in September 2022 led to a useful debate inside the firm and the decisio=
n to exit most of that business. (One part of Goldman=E2=80=99s foray into =
consumer banking that remains intact is =E2=80=9CMarcus,=E2=80=9D its onlin=
e deposit-gathering mechanism, which is still an important source of relati=
vely inexpensive
financing for the bank.)<br/><br/>While parts of the investment banking bus=
iness, such as equity capital markets, I.P.O.s, and M&amp;A, are still well=
 below their 10-year average volumes, Waldron told me that people at Goldma=
n are busier than they=E2=80=99ve been in the recent past. =E2=80=9CActivit=
y is up,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CIt just feels better. And we=E2=80=99ve=
 turned the corner on losses in the consumer strategy, which I think was ge=
nerating a lot of angst.=E2=80=9D As a result, I=E2=80=99m sure, in the som=
ewhat convoluted way of thinking on Wall Street, Goldman=E2=80=99s bankers =
and traders are happier and believe they are going to get bigger bonuses co=
me January. <br/></td>
