         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s5">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">What Waldron says a=
bout Goldman and its future matters. At 55, he=E2=80=99s well positioned to=
 succeed the 62-year-old Solomon, a fellow Bear Stearns alum, whenever that=
 transition takes place, having been Solomon=E2=80=99s right-hand man since=
 David succeeded <b>Lloyd Blankfein</b>. (Lloyd, who never went to Washingt=
on, is putting the finishing touches on a memoir about his life and time at=
 Goldman, written with <b>Jacob Weisberg</b>, who was also the ghostwriter =
on <b>Bob Rubin</b>=E2=80=99s memoir.) Goldman=E2=80=99s focus, according t=
o Waldron, is to grow the =E2=80=9Cwallet share=E2=80=9D in its core bankin=
g and trading businesses, which have been performing well. He said Goldman =
wants to become a bigger =E2=80=9Cfinancier=E2=80=9D of businesses. =E2=80=
=9CWe think there=E2=80=99s a huge secular growth opportunity in financing,=
=E2=80=9D he said, whether it be leveraged buyouts or to provide financing =
to
alternative asset managers such as Apollo, Blackstone, and KKR. =E2=80=9CYo=
u=E2=80=99re going to see us be=E2=80=94and we already have become=E2=80=94=
much more ambitious in our desire to finance,=E2=80=9D Waldron said. <br/><=
br/>Goldman=E2=80=99s prudential regulator, the Federal Reserve, seems not =
to object to the big Wall Street banks providing financing, because it help=
s businesses grow and stimulates economic growth. What it doesn=E2=80=99t l=
ike, and what Goldman seems to be doing less of these days, is betting on t=
he direction of commodity prices or mortgage yields. <br/><br/>At the partn=
er offsite in Miami this past February, the firm allowed its top leaders to=
 share with the firm=E2=80=99s executives their thoughts about the firm=E2=
=80=99s strategy. =E2=80=9CWe sort of reframed that it=E2=80=99s kind of Go=
ldman Sachs being Goldman Sachs,=E2=80=9D Waldron said. =E2=80=9CMaybe Gold=
man Sachs being Goldman Sachs, 2.0=E2=80=A6 We=E2=80=99re going to go back =
to doing the things that we=E2=80=99re really good at, where we have a righ=
t to win, and reinvesting back into
those capabilities and being one Goldman Sachs in as many places that we ca=
n be. The execution of it is not simple, but it=E2=80=99s not that complica=
ted a strategy.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>Waldron also defended Goldman=E2=80=99s =
rather outspoken demand that people return to the office as quickly as was =
permissible after the pandemic. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re a very human, connec=
ted firm,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re not a Zoom firm. We need=
 to be together around the proverbial table.=E2=80=9D He said Goldman=E2=80=
=99s people =E2=80=9Cpretty much up and down the spectrum=E2=80=9D are happ=
y to be back in the office. =E2=80=9CI actually think we=E2=80=99ve done a =
good job navigating that,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CWe might have been a l=
ittle loud initially, and maybe we could have narrated that a little differ=
ently as a firm, but I think generally speaking, we were right, and our peo=
ple are happy to be back, and they recognize that we=E2=80=99re a firm that=
 operates best in that vein.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>He=E2=80=99s optimistic abo=
ut Goldman and its future prospects, of course,
especially now that Goldman Sachs is back to being Goldman Sachs. =E2=80=9C=
We=E2=80=99re pleased with where we are,=E2=80=9D he said. =E2=80=9CThere=
=E2=80=99s a lot of opportunity. Markets are getting better.=E2=80=9D He sa=
id he thinks investors expect Goldman will get its fair share, or more, of =
the investment banking business as markets continue to recover and if the e=
conomy achieves the much-anticipated soft landing, which certainly seems to=
 be the case at the moment. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re executing,=E2=80=9D he s=
aid. =E2=80=9COur people feel good. They know what we=E2=80=99re trying to =
do. We=E2=80=99re on our way to continuing to do well there.=E2=80=9D <br/>=
<br/>He also told me that Goldman=E2=80=99s banking and trading businesses =
are generating 16 percent average return-on-equity (a Wall Street measure o=
f profitability and performance), =E2=80=9Cwhich is pretty attractive. I do=
n=E2=80=99t think anybody else is doing better in that business than we are=
=2E=E2=80=9D And he said the banking b=
usiness has =E2=80=9Ccyclical growth=E2=
=80=9D=E2=80=94it will rebound as the economy continues to
grow=E2=80=94while the asset and wealth management side of Goldman=E2=80=99=
s business is experiencing =E2=80=9Csecular growth=E2=80=9D of two times G.=
D.P. growth =E2=80=9Cor maybe a little more,=E2=80=9D he said. That=E2=80=
=99s where, he continued, =E2=80=9Cwe are seeing real significant opportuni=
ties for growth.=E2=80=9D He concluded, =E2=80=9CThe fact is, those are the=
 only two things we=E2=80=99re doing. We=E2=80=99re not doing anything else=
=2E Those are the two businesses. We=
=E2=80=99re just going to run that play.=
=E2=80=9D<br/><br/>How it all plays out at Goldman remains to be seen, of c=
ourse. There are any number of exogenous events that could derail the Goldm=
an playbook, including parts of the financial markets that have less liquid=
ity than Waldron would like to see, or cyberattacks, another worry, or U.S.=
-China relations, a perennial concern, and of course geopolitics generally =
surrounding the outcome of the U.S. presidential election. =E2=80=9CThere=
=E2=80=99s a lot to worry about,=E2=80=9D he said, =E2=80=9Cbut right now, =
the markets are plowing through all that stuff
without a lot of risk premium.=E2=80=9D <br/><br/>Mayo told me he thinks Go=
ldman has finally turned the corner after a bit of a bad patch. He said the=
 conversation around Goldman has changed in the last year from <i>Can David=
 Solomon survive</i>? to <i>How much money can Goldman make?</i> =E2=80=9CW=
hen you talk Goldman,=E2=80=9D Mayo said, =E2=80=9Cthe discussion now is le=
ss, <i>What is Goldman doing to better position itself?</i>, and more: <i>H=
ow is the market transpiring to the benefit or detriment of Goldman?.</i> T=
he discussion now is about the markets, not about Goldman Sachs.=E2=80=9D<b=
r/></td>
         </tr>
